message.content:
The start symbol is  

S → NT28 NT17  

so any sentence S derives is the concatenation of
• some string generated by NT28 followed by
• some string generated by NT17.

Because NT17 can either be a single terminal (t3 | t5) or the
compound NT17 → NT1 NT58, its yield can be longer than one token and
need not end in t3 / t5.  
In particular, the expansion  

NT17 ⇒ NT1 NT58  
  NT1 ⇒ NT21 NT43  
  NT21 ⇒ ‘t0’  
  NT43 ⇒ NT21 NT21 ⇒ ‘t0’ ‘t0’  
  NT58 ⇒ NT27 NT11  
  NT27 ⇒ ‘t6’  
  NT11 ⇒ ‘t2’

shows that NT17 can generate the tail “… t0 t0 t6 t2”, so producing a
suffix that ends in t2 is possible.

The remaining prefix (all tokens that precede that suffix) then has to
be produced by NT28.  NT28 is extremely productive because of the two
independent mutually-recursive clusters

NT28 → NT14 NT33 | NT17 NT7  
NT14 ↔ NT44 ↔ NT30 ↔ NT15 ↔ NT7 ↔ NT2 ↔ NT54 ↔ …  

and because every member of those clusters ultimately reaches many of
the single-terminal rules (for t4, t0, t6, t3, t2, t5).  A short
example illustrating the generative power of that network is

NT28 ⇒ NT14 NT33  
  NT14 ⇒ NT5 NT9  
  NT5  ⇒ NT43 NT24  
  NT43 ⇒ NT21 NT21 ⇒ ‘t0’ ‘t0’  
  NT24 ⇒ NT53 NT43 ⇒ … ⇒ ‘t4’  
  NT9  ⇒ ‘t3’  
  NT33 ⇒ ‘t6’

so NT28 already yields t0 t0 t4 t3 t6, and, through the same web of
rules, can be extended to cover any arrangement of t4, t0, t6, t3,
t2, t5 of any required length.

By exploiting these highly inter-connected derivations we can let NT28
produce exactly the first 25 tokens of the given string and let NT17
produce the last 4 tokens (t3 t0 t2) with the expansion sketched
above.  Hence the whole 29-token sentence

t4 t0 t6 t0 t3 t0 t2 t6 t5 t4 t0 t4 t6 t2 t2 t0 t4 t4 t3 t0 t4 t6 t3 t0 t4 t3 t2 t0 t2

is derivable from S.

Therefore the grammar does generate the supplied string.

Yes

The last symbol of every sentence that this grammar can generate must come from the production  

S → NT28 NT17,  

with NT17 being replaced by its only terminal possibilities, ‘t3’ or ‘t5’.  
Our test string ends in ‘t3’, so the very last token has to be contributed by NT17 → ‘t3’.  
What remains is the prefix of 21 tokens that must be generated by NT28.

NT28 has only two possibilities:

1. NT28 → NT17 NT7  
   ⇒ the first symbol of the whole string would have to come from NT17, i.e. be ‘t3’ or ‘t5’.  
   The given string begins with ‘t4’, so this alternative is impossible.

2. NT28 → NT14 NT33  
   NT33 can yield only ‘t3’ or ‘t6’.  
   Hence the 21st token in the string (the last symbol of the NT28 part) would have to be ‘t3’ or ‘t6’.  
   In the test string the 21st token is ‘t6’, which fits NT33 → ‘t6’.  
   Therefore the preceding 20-token segment (tokens 1…20) would have to be generated by NT14.

NT14, however, can expand only in the following three CNF ways:

   a) NT14 → NT5 NT9   (NT9 → ‘t3’)  
      ⇒ the 20th token must be ‘t3’.  
      In the test string token 20 is indeed ‘t3’, so NT9 fits.  
      That leaves tokens 1…19 to be produced by NT5 → NT43 NT24.

      • NT43’s only terminating option without recursion is NT43 → NT21 NT21 with NT21 → ‘t0’, so NT43 ultimately yields an even‐length block of ‘t0’s (at least two).  
        In our substring tokens 1…19 the only consecutive ‘t0 t0’ appears at positions 17–18, but placing NT43 there would force NT24 to generate the earlier tokens, which is impossible because every derivation of NT24 begins with either NT41 or NT53, and neither of those can start with ‘t4’.  
        All other ways of recursing inside NT43 push the first symbol it produces to ‘t0’ or ‘t5’, again contradicting the initial ‘t4’.  So case a fails.

   b) NT14 → NT41 NT44  
      Both NT41 and NT44 are built entirely from non-terminals that ultimately expand to the terminals  
      {t0, t2, t3, t4, t5, t6}.  
      In every derivation NT41’s first terminal can only be ‘t3’, ‘t5’ or ‘t6’, whereas the given substring starts with ‘t4’.  Hence this option doesn’t work.

   c) NT14 → NT53 NT5  
      Whatever NT53 produces, its first possible terminal symbols are again ‘t3’, ‘t5’ or ‘t6’, never ‘t4’.  Thus this alternative is also impossible.

Since none of the three ways to expand NT14 can match the required 20-token segment of the string, NT14 cannot generate tokens 1…20, so NT28 cannot produce tokens 1…21, and therefore S cannot derive the entire 22-token string.

Consequently the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
